public static int[] findCommonElements(int[]... arrays) {
    if (arrays.length == 0) {
        return new int[0];
    }

    List<Integer> commonElements = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < arrays[0].length; i++) {
        int element = arrays[0][i];
        boolean foundInAllArrays = true;
        for (int j = 1; j < arrays.length; j++) {
            if (!contains(arrays[j], element)) {
                foundInAllArrays = false;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (foundInAllArrays) {
            commonElements.add(element);
        }
    }

    return commonElements.stream().mapToInt(Integer::intValue).toArray();
}

private static boolean contains(int[] array, int element) {
    for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
        if (array[i] == element) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}

<<<explanation>>>:
This code first checks if the input arrays are empty. If so, it returns an empty array. Otherwise, it iterates through the first array and checks if each element is present in all other arrays. If it is, it adds it to a list of common elements. Finally, it converts the list to an array and returns it.

